83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
Senate Bill 1547
Ordered by the Senate February 9
Including Senate Amendments dated February 9
Printed pursuant to Senate Interim Rule 213.28 by order of the President of the Senate in conformance with pre-
session filing rules, indicating neither advocacy nor opposition on the part of the President (at the request
of Senate Interim Committee on Early Childhood and Behavioral Health for The Ballmer Institute for
Children’s Behavioral Health at the University of Oregon)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act makes a new profession called a licensed behavioral health and wellness prac-
titioner. The Act says what the licensee can do. The Act also says that the licensee has to report
some kinds of abuse. (Flesch Readability Score: 67.7).
Authorizes the Oregon Board of Psychology to issue a license to practice behavioral health
promotion, prevention and brief intervention to a qualified applicant. Defines the “practice of be-
havioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention” and “licensed behavioral health and
wellness practitioner.” Prohibits a person from using the title “licensed behavioral health and
wellness practitioner” without a license.
Creates a licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner-client privilege for certain com-
munications. Requires a licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner to report certain types
of abuse.
Takes effect on the 91st day following adjournment sine die.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioners; creating new provisions; amending
3 ORS 124.050, 192.556, 414.025, 419B.005, 430.735, 609.652, 675.010, 675.075, 675.085, 675.087,
4 675.110, 675.115, 675.130, 675.140, 675.145, 675.150, 675.166, 675.178, 675.661 and 675.850; and
5 prescribing an effective date.
6 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
7
8 LICENSED BEHAVIORAL HEALTH AND
9 WELLNESS PRACTITIONERS
10
11 SECTION 1. As used in sections 1 to 7 of this 2026 Act:
12 (1) “Licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner” means an individual licensed
13 under section 2 of this 2026 Act to practice behavioral health promotion, prevention and brief
14 intervention.
15 (2) “Licensed psychologist” has the meaning given that term in ORS 675.010.
16 (3) “Practice of behavioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention” includes
17 the provision of the following services, either directly or indirectly, in an individual or group
18 format, with or without client caregivers or families:
19 (a) Early identification of behavioral health concerns, including identification through the
20 use of behavioral health screening;
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 111

A-Eng. SB 1547
1 (b) Psychoeducation;
2 (c) Skills training and skills support;
3 (d) Brief, evidence-based behavioral health interventions and prevention services;
4 (e) Risk identification and referral; and
5 (f) Collaboration, consultation and care coordination with other behavioral health pro-
6 viders.
7 SECTION 2. (1) The Oregon Board of Psychology may issue a license to practice behav-
8 ioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention to an applicant who:
9 (a)(A) Holds a bachelor’s degree or higher in behavioral health from a program approved
10 by the board that includes at least 700 hours of supervised practice in the delivery of be-
11 havioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention services; or
12 (B) Holds a bachelor’s degree or higher in a field other than behavioral health if the ap-
13 plicant has also completed an educational program approved by the board that includes at
14 least 700 hours of supervised practice in the delivery of behavioral health promotion, pre-
15 vention and brief intervention services;
16 (b) Has successfully completed any training required by the board by rule;
17 (c) Passes, to the satisfaction of the board, an examination required by the board by rule;
18 (d) Is determined by the board to be of good moral character, as described in ORS 675.030;
19 (e) Pays an application fee; and
20 (f) Meets other requirements established by the board by rule.
21 (2) The supervised practice described in subsection (1) of this section must be performed
22 under the supervision of an individual described in section 4 of this 2026 Act.
23 (3) The board may adopt rules to establish requirements for the renewal of a license is-
24 sued under this section.
25 (4) Moneys from fees collected under this section shall be deposited in the Oregon Board
26 of Psychology Account established under ORS 675.140.
27 SECTION 3. An individual whose license issued under section 2 of this 2026 Act has ex-
28 pired may apply as follows to the Oregon Board of Psychology to be relicensed:
29 (1) If the previous license has been expired for more than two years, the individual must
30 apply and qualify for the new license in the same manner as an individual who has never
31 been licensed.
32 (2)(a) If the previous license has been expired for two years or less, the individual must:
33 (A) Apply for relicensure in a manner required by the board;
34 (B) Meet any requirements for relicensure established by the board by rule; and
35 (C) Pay the fee established by the board.
36 (b) An individual who applies for relicensure under paragraph (a) of this subsection may
37 not be required to meet the requirements described in section 2 (1)(a) to (c) of this 2026 Act.
38 SECTION 4. (1) A licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner may practice be-
39 havioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention only under the direct super-
40 vision of a:
41 (a) Licensed psychologist;
42 (b) Physician licensed under ORS chapter 677 who has a specialty in psychiatry;
43 (c) Licensed professional counselor, as defined in ORS 675.705;
44 (d) Licensed marriage and family therapist, as defined in ORS 675.705;
45 (e) Clinical social worker licensed under ORS 675.530; or
[2]

A-Eng. SB 1547
1 (f) Nurse practitioner licensed under ORS 678.375 to 678.390 who has a specialty in psy-
2 chiatric mental health.
3 (2) The Oregon Board of Psychology may adopt rules to carry out this section, including
4 rules to establish requirements for supervision and a process for an individual described in
5 subsection (1) of this section to be an approved supervisor.
6 SECTION 5. An individual may not use the title “licensed behavioral health and wellness
7 practitioner” or similar title or initials unless the individual is a licensed behavioral health
8 and wellness practitioner.
9 SECTION 6. A licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner may not:
10 (1) Engage in the practice of psychology, as described in ORS 675.010;
11 (2) Practice medicine, as described in ORS 677.085;
12 (3) Diagnose any physical, behavioral, emotional or mental disorder;
13 (4) Independently treat any physical, behavioral, emotional or mental disorder;
14 (5) Administer or interpret any individually administered intelligence, academic achieve-
15 ment or neuropscyhological tests; or
16 (6) Evaluate the effects of any medical or psychotropic drugs.
17 SECTION 7. (1) If any of the grounds enumerated in subsection (2) of this section exist,
18 the Oregon Board of Psychology may impose any of the following sanctions:
19 (a) Deny a license to practice behavioral health promotion, prevention and brief inter-
20 vention;
21 (b) Refuse to renew or suspend or revoke a license to practice behavioral health pro-
22 motion, prevention and brief intervention;
23 (c) Issue a letter of reprimand;
24 (d) Impose probation with authority to require practice under increased supervision; or
25 (e) Impose a civil penalty as described under subsection (3) of this section.
26 (2) Subject to subsection (7) of this section, the board may impose a sanction listed in
27 subsection (1) of this section against a licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner,
28 an applicant for a license to practice behavioral health promotion, prevention and brief
29 intervention or, if applicable, an unlicensed individual found in violation of sections 1 to 7 of
30 this 2026 Act, if, in the board’s judgment, the licensee, applicant or individual:
31 (a) Has an impairment as defined in ORS 676.303;
32 (b) Has been convicted of a violation of law related to controlled substances;
33 (c) Has been convicted of a felony or misdemeanor involving moral turpitude;
34 (d) Is guilty of immoral or unprofessional conduct or of gross negligence in the practice
35 of behavioral health promotion, prevention and brief intervention, including but not limited
36 to:
37 (A) Conduct or practice contrary to recognized standards of ethics of the profession or
38 that constitutes a danger to the health or safety of a patient or the public;
39 (B) Conduct, practice or a condition that adversely affects the ability of a licensed be-
40 havioral health and wellness practitioner or an applicant for a license to practice behavioral
41 health promotion, prevention and brief intervention to practice safely and skillfully; or
42 (C) Having practiced outside the authorized scope of practice for a licensed behavioral
43 health and wellness practitioner;
44 (e) Has obtained, or attempted to obtain, a license to practice behavioral health pro-
45 motion, prevention and brief intervention by fraud or material misrepresentation;
