21 BEHAVIORAL HEALTH AND WELLNESS PRACTITIONER-CLIENT PRIVILEGE
22
23 SECTION 22. Section 23 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS 40.225 to
24 40.295.
25 SECTION 23. A licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner licensed by the
26 Oregon Board of Psychology under section 2 of this 2026 Act shall not be examined in a civil
27 or criminal court proceeding as to any communication given to the licensed behavioral health
28 and wellness practitioner by a client in the course of a noninvestigatory professional activity
29 when the communication was given to enable the licensed behavioral health and wellness
30 practitioner to aid the client, except:
31 (1) When the client or those persons legally responsible for the affairs of the client give
32 consent to the disclosure;
33 (2) When the client initiates legal action to make a complaint against the board or the
34 licensed behavioral health and wellness practitioner;
35 (3) When the communication reveals the intent to commit a crime or harmful act; or
36 (4) When the communication reveals that a minor is, or is suspected to be, the victim
37 of a crime, abuse or neglect.
38 SECTION 24. (1) Section 23 of this 2026 Act becomes operative on January 1, 2027.
39 (2) The Oregon Board of Psychology may take any action before the operative date
40 specified in subsection (1) of this section that is necessary to enable the board to exercise,
41 on and after the operative date specified in subsection (1) of this section, all of the duties,
42 functions and powers conferred on the board by section 23 of this 2026 Act.
43
44 ABUSE REPORTING
45
[9]

A-Eng. SB 1547
1 SECTION 25. ORS 124.050 is amended to read:
2 124.050. As used in ORS 124.050 to 124.095:
3 (1) “Abuse” means one or more of the following:
4 (a) Any physical injury to an elderly person caused by other than accidental means, or which
5 appears to be at variance with the explanation given of the injury.
6 (b) Neglect.
7 (c) Abandonment, including desertion or willful forsaking of an elderly person or the withdrawal
8 or neglect of duties and obligations owed an elderly person by a caretaker or other person.
9 (d) Willful infliction of physical pain or injury upon an elderly person.
10 (e) An act that constitutes a crime under ORS 163.375, 163.405, 163.411, 163.415, 163.425, 163.427,
11 163.465, 163.467 or 163.525.
12 (f) Verbal abuse.
13 (g) Financial exploitation.
14 (h) Sexual abuse.
15 (i) Involuntary seclusion of an elderly person for the convenience of a caregiver or to discipline
16 the person.
17 (j) A wrongful use of a physical or chemical restraint of an elderly person, excluding an act of
18 restraint prescribed by a physician licensed under ORS chapter 677 and any treatment activities
19 that are consistent with an approved treatment plan or in connection with a court order.
20 (2) “Elderly person” means any person 65 years of age or older who is not subject to the pro-
21 visions of ORS 441.640 to 441.665.
22 (3) “Facility” means:
23 (a) A long term care facility as that term is defined in ORS 442.015.
24 (b) A residential facility as that term is defined in ORS 443.400, including but not limited to an
25 assisted living facility.
26 (c) An adult foster home as that term is defined in ORS 443.705.
27 (4) “Financial exploitation” means:
28 (a) Wrongfully taking the assets, funds or property belonging to or intended for the use of an
29 elderly person or a person with a disability.
30 (b) Alarming an elderly person or a person with a disability by conveying a threat to wrongfully
31 take or appropriate money or property of the person if the person would reasonably believe that the
32 threat conveyed would be carried out.
33 (c) Misappropriating, misusing or transferring without authorization any money from any ac-
34 count held jointly or singly by an elderly person or a person with a disability.
35 (d) Failing to use the income or assets of an elderly person or a person with a disability effec-
36 tively for the support and maintenance of the person.
37 (5) “Intimidation” means compelling or deterring conduct by threat.
38 (6) “Law enforcement agency” means:
39 (a) Any city or municipal police department.
40 (b) Any county sheriff’s office.
41 (c) The Oregon State Police.
42 (d) Any district attorney.
43 (e) A police department established by a university under ORS 352.121 or 353.125.
44 (7) “Neglect” means failure to provide basic care or services that are necessary to maintain the
45 health or safety of an elderly person.
